Think of a Promise as a placeholder for a value that you‚Äôll get later.
const pizzaOrder = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    const isPizzaReady = true;
    if (isPizzaReady) {
      resolve("Pizza is ready!");
    } else {
      reject("Sorry, no pizza today.");
    }
  }, 3000);
});

pizzaOrder
  .then((message) => console.log(message))
  .catch((error) => console.error(error));

Here, .then() is like, ‚ÄúWhat do I do when the pizza arrives?‚Äù and .catch() is, ‚ÄúWhat if it doesn‚Äôt?‚Äù
JavaScript is single-threaded ‚Äî it can do one thing at a time. Promises help us avoid blocking things while waiting for slower tasks (like API calls or timers).
Instead of freezing the app, Promises let JavaScript say, ‚ÄúI‚Äôll come back to this when it‚Äôs ready,‚Äù and keep moving.
